Tennessee Republican Alexander, along with Democrats, criticized White House-backed driver's license rules before the Senate unanimously approved an $82 billion spending bill.
The rules, authored by Rep. Sensenbrenner, aim to enhance license security but face opposition from states due to cost concerns and privacy issues.
Immigrant rights groups denounce the legislation as anti-immigrant, reflecting a hostile climate post-9/11.
Critics argue for comprehensive immigration reform instead of focusing on driver's licenses.
The Real ID Act, part of the bill, imposes strict ID requirements, sparking debates on privacy, security, and national ID cards.
